conversation_a.content:
Here are some examples in C code to illustrate good and bad usage of GOTO statements:

Bad GOTO example:

```c
int func() {
  int x = 0;

  if(x > 0) 
    goto label;

  // do something

  label: 
  x++;

  if(x < 10)
    goto label;

  // rest of function
}
```

This uses GOTO for arbitrary jumps around the function, harming readability.

Good structured example without GOTO:

```c 
int func() {

  for(int x = 0; x < 10; x++) {
    // loop body 
  }

  if(condition) {
    // if block
  } else {
    // else block 
  }

  return 0;
}
```

This uses standard control structures like for loops and if/else that are easier to follow.

Even better:

```c
void loop() {
  while(1) {
    func1();
    func2(); 
  }
}

int func1() {
  //...
}

int func2() {
  //... 
}
``` 

This divides the problem into well-defined functions with single entry/exit points rather than monolithic code with GOTO.

In general, C code that avoids unnecessary GOTO jumps and uses standard control structures, modular functions and clear flow is better structured according to this design principle.

conversation_b.content:
Here are some examples of good and bad uses of GOTO statements in C:

Bad:

```c
void function() {
  // ...
  if (error) {
    goto error;
  }

  // ...

error:
  printError();
  cleanup();
  return;
}
```

- Using GOTO for error handling makes the control flow hard to follow. Better to use return values.

Bad: 

```c
for (i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
  for (j = 0; j < 20; j++) {
    if (j == 15) {
      goto end;
    }
  }
}

end:
printf("Done");
```

- GOTO jumps out of nested loop, bypassing increment of i. Unstructured control flow.

Good:

```c  
for (i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
  for (j = 0; j < 20; j++) {
    if (j == 15) {
      break;
    }
  }
}
```

- Using break statement to break out of loop is clearer.

Good:

```c
void print_matrix() {
  for (i = 0; i < N; i++) {
    for (j = 0; j < M; j++) {
      if (matrix[i][j] == 0) {
        goto skip;
      }
      printf("%d ", matrix[i][j]);

skip: ;
    }
  }
}
```

- GOTO used for optimization to skip printing zeros. Limited scope and intent is clear.

So in C, it's best to avoid GOTO if possible, but limited usage for simple branching may be justified.

